{
  "answer": "In Mirza Ghalib's ghazal, the opening couplet hinges on *jigar*'s position as the body's deepest core (below the heart/*dil*), into which the beloved's glance piercingly descends (*utar gayi*), subduing both organs' resistance in one graceful blow.[^1]\n\n**Transliteration:**  \nDil se teri nigāh jigar tak utar gayī  \nDono ko ik adā meṃ razām̤and kar gayī[^2]\n\n**Translation:**  \nYour glance passed from my heart into my core;  \nWith a single charm, their will to fight is gone.\n\n[^1]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, ch. 35 [\"Dil se teri nigaah jigar tak utar gayi\"](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/35-dil-se-teri-nigaah-jigar-tak-utar-gayi/translation/#p-4ab0d4).\n\n[^2]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, ch. 35 [\"Dil se teri nigaah jigar tak utar gayi\"](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/35-dil-se-teri-nigaah-jigar-tak-utar-gayi/transliteration/#p-cd48f5).",
